<div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert dark"><h3 data-start="0" data-end="59"><strong data-start="4" data-end="57">Boyce-Codd Normal Form (BCNF) â€“ Stronger than 3NF</strong></h3><h4 data-start="61" data-end="83"><strong data-start="66" data-end="81">Definition:</strong></h4><p data-start="84" data-end="112">A table is in <strong data-start="98" data-end="106">BCNF</strong> if:</p><ol data-start="113" data-end="225"><li data-start="113" data-end="178"><strong data-start="116" data-end="140">It is already in 3NF</strong> (i.e., no transitive dependencies).</li><li data-start="179" data-end="225"><strong data-start="182" data-end="223">Every determinant is a candidate key.</strong></li></ol><p data-start="227" data-end="433">A <strong data-start="229" data-end="244">determinant</strong> is an attribute (or set of attributes) that uniquely determines another attribute.<br data-start="327" data-end="330">A <strong data-start="332" data-end="349">candidate key</strong> is a minimal set ofttributes that can uniquely identify every row in the table.</p><p data-start="435" data-end="523">BCNF fixes cases where <strong data-start="458" data-end="522">3NF still allows anomalies due to overlapping candidate keys</strong>.</p><hr data-start="525" data-end="528"><h2 data-start="530" data-end="584"><strong data-start="533" data-end="584">Different Ways a Table Can Violate BCNF &amp; Fixes</strong></h2><h3 data-start="586" data-end="653"><strong data-start="590" data-end="651">Set 1: Professor-Course Example (Multiple Candidate Keys)</strong></h3><h4 data-start="654" data-end="680">âŒ <strong data-start="661" data-end="680">Violating BCNF:</strong></h4><table data-start="681" data-end="857"><thead data-start="681" data-end="717"><tr data-start="681" data-end="717"><th data-start="681" data-end="693">Professor</th><th data-start="693" data-end="704">Course</th><th data-start="704" data-end="717">Classroom</th></tr></thead><tbody data-start="753" data-end="857"><tr data-start="753" data-end="787"><td>DrSmith</td><td>Math</td><td>A101</td></tr><tr data-start="788" data-end="822"><td>Dr. Jones</td><td>English</td><td>B202</td></tr><tr data-start="823" data-end="857"><td>Dr. Smith</td><td>Physics</td><td>A101</td></tr></tbody></table><p data-start="859" data-end="876">ğŸ”´ <strong data-start="862" data-end="874">Problem:</strong></p><ul data-start="877" data-end="1140"><li data-start="877" data-end="938">A <strong data-start="881" data-end="935">professor teaches a course in a specific classroom</strong>.</li><li data-start="939" data-end="1011"><strong data-start="941" data-end="960">Candidate keys:</strong> <code data-start="961" data-end="982">{Professor, Course}</code> and <code data-start="987" data-end="1008">{Classroom, Course}</code>.</li><li data-start="1012" data-end="1140"><strong data-start="1014" data-end="1036">Determinant issue:</strong> <code data-start="1037" data-end="1060">Classroom â†’ Professor</code> (Classroom uniquely determines Professor, but it is <strong data-start="1113" data-end="1not a candidate key</strong>).</li></ul><h4 data-start="1142" data-end="1182">âœ… <strong data-start="1149" data-end="1180">Fix (Split into Two Tables)</strong></h4><p data-start="1183" data-end="1213">âœ” <strong data-start="1185" data-end="1211">Professor-Course Table</strong></p><table data-start="1214" data-end="1331"><thead data-start="1214" data-end="1237"><tr data-start="1214" data-end="1237"><th data-start="1214" data-end="1226">Professor</th><th data-start="1226" data-end="1237">Course</th></tr></thead><tbody data-start="1261" data-end="1331"><tr data-start="1261" data-end="1283"><td>Dr. Smith</td><td>Math</td></tr><tr data-start="1284" data-end="1307"><td>Dr. Jones</td><td>English</td></tr><tr data-start="1308" data-end="1331"><td>Dr. Smith</td><td>Physics</td></tr></tbody></table><p data-start="1333" data-end="1366">âœ” <strong data-start="1335" data-end="1364">Classroom-Professor Table</strong></p><table data-start="1367" data-end="1473"><thead data-start="1367" data-end="1393"><tr data-start="136a-end="1393"><th data-start="1367" data-end="1379">Classroom</th><th data-start="1379" data-end="1393">Professor</th></tr></thead><tbody data-start="1420" data-end="1473"><tr data-start="1420" data-end="1446"><td>A101</td><td>Dr. Smith</td></tr><tr data-start="1447" data-end="1473"><td>B202</td><td>Dr. Jones</td></tr></tbody></table><p data-start="1475" data-end="1509">âœ… Now, the tables are in <strong data-start="1500" data-end="1508">BCNF</strong>.</p><hr data-start="1511" data-end="1514"><h3 data-start="1516" data-end="1598"><strong data-start="1520" data-end="1596">Set 2: Employee-Project Example (BCNF Violation Due to Overlapping Keys)</strong></h3><h4 data-start="1599" data-end="1625">âŒ <strong data-start="1606" data-end="1625">Violating BCNF:</strong></h4><table data-start="1626" data-end="1793"><thead data-start="1626" data-end="1661"><tr data-start="1626" data-end="1661"><th data-start="1626" data-end="1640">Employee_ID</th><th data-start="1640" data-end="1650">Project</th><th data-start="1650" dand="1661">Manager</th></tr></thead><tbody data-start="1695" data-end="1793"><tr data-start="1695" data-end="1727"><td>E1</td><td>P1</td><td>M1</td></tr><tr data-start="1728" data-end="1760"><td>E2</td><td>P2</td><td>M2</td></tr><tr data-start="1761" data-end="1793"><td>E1</td><td>P3</td><td>M1</td></tr></tbody></table><p data-start="1795" data-end="1812">ğŸ”´ <strong data-start="1798" data-end="1810">Problem:</strong></p><ul data-start="1813" data-end="2080"><li data-start="1813" data-end="1877">An <strong data-start="1818" data-end="1874">employee works on a project under a specific manager</strong>.</li><li data-start="1878" data-end="1952"><strong data-start="1880" data-end="1899">Candidate keys:</strong> <code data-start="1900" data-end="1924">{Employee_ID, Project}</code> and <code data-start="1929" data-end="1949">{Project, Manager}</code>.</li><li data-start="1953" data-end="2080"><strong data-start="1955" data-end="1977">Determinant issue:</strong> <code data-start="1978" data-end="1997">Project â†’ Mr</code> (Project uniquely determines Manager, but <code data-start="2040" data-end="2049">Project</code> is <strong data-start="2053" data-end="2076">not a candidate key</strong>).</li></ul><h4 data-start="2082" data-end="2122">âœ… <strong data-start="2089" data-end="2120">Fix (Split into Two Tables)</strong></h4><p data-start="2123" data-end="2153">âœ” <strong data-start="2125" data-end="2151">Employee-Project Table</strong></p><table data-start="2154" data-end="2276"><thead data-start="2154" data-end="2180"><tr data-start="2154" data-end="2180"><th data-start="2154" data-end="2168">Employee_ID</th><th data-start="2168" data-end="2180">Project</th></tr></thead><tbody data-start="2205" data-end="2276"><tr data-start="2205" data-end="2228"><td>E1</td><td>P1</td></tr><tr data-start="2229" data-end="2252"><td>E2</td><td>P2</td></tr><tr data-start="2253" data-end="2276"><td>E1</td><td>P3</td></tr></tbody></table><p data-start="2278" data-end="2307">âœ” <strong data-start="2280" data-end="2305">Project-Manager Tatrong></p><table data-start="2308" data-end="2409"><thead data-start="2308" data-end="2329"><tr data-start="2308" data-end="2329"><th data-start="2308" data-end="2318">Project</th><th data-start="2318" data-end="2329">Manager</th></tr></thead><tbody data-start="2350" data-end="2409"><tr data-start="2350" data-end="2369"><td>P1</td><td>M1</td></tr><tr data-start="2370" data-end="2389"><td>P2</td><td>M2</td></tr><tr data-start="2390" data-end="2409"><td>P3</td><td>M1</td></tr></tbody></table><p data-start="2411" data-end="2445">âœ… Now, the tables are in <strong data-start="2436" data-end="2444">BCNF</strong>.</p><hr data-start="2447" data-end="2450"><h3 data-start="2452" data-end="2519"><strong data-start="2456" data-end="2517">Set 3: Student-Club Example (Functional Dependency Issue)</strong></h3><h4 data-start="2520" data-end="2546">âŒ <strong data-start="2527" data-end="2546">Violating BCNF:</strong></h4><table data-start="2547" data-end="2735"><thead data-start="2547" data-end="2587"><tr data-start="2547"a-end="2587"><th data-start="2547" data-end="2560">Student_ID</th><th data-start="2560" data-end="2569">Club</th><th data-start="2569" data-end="2587">Club_President</th></tr></thead><tbody data-start="2625" data-end="2735"><tr data-start="2625" data-end="2661"><td>101</td><td>Music</td><td>Alice</td></tr><tr data-start="2662" data-end="2698"><td>102</td><td>Drama</td><td>Bob</td></tr><tr data-start="2699" data-end="2735"><td>103</td><td>Music</td><td>Alice</td></tr></tbody></table><p data-start="2737" data-end="2754">ğŸ”´ <strong data-start="2740" data-end="2752">Problem:</strong></p><ul data-start="2755" data-end="3004"><li data-start="2755" data-end="2828">A <strong data-start="2759" data-end="2783">student joins a club</strong>, and each <strong data-start="2794" data-end="2825">club has a single president</strong>.</li><li data-start="2829" data-end="2873"><strong data-start="2831" data-end="2849">Candidate key:</strong> <code data-start="2850" data-end="2870">{Student_ID, Club}</code>.</li><li data-star2874" data-end="3004"><strong data-start="2876" data-end="2898">Determinant issue:</strong> <code data-start="2899" data-end="2922">Club â†’ Club_President</code> (Club uniquely determines Club_President, but Club is <strong data-start="2977" data-end="3000">not a candidate key</strong>).</li></ul><h4 data-start="3006" data-end="3054">âœ… <strong data-start="3013" data-end="3052">Fix (Separate Clubs and Presidents)</strong></h4><p data-start="3055" data-end="3081">âœ” <strong data-start="3057" data-end="3079">Student-Club Table</strong></p><table data-start="3082" data-end="3193"><thead data-start="3082" data-end="3105"><tr data-start="3082" data-end="3105"><th data-start="3082" data-end="3095">Student_ID</th><th data-start="3095" data-end="3105">Club</th></tr></thead><tbody data-start="3128" data-end="3193"><tr data-start="3128" data-end="3149"><td>101</td><td>Music</td></tr><tr data-start="3150" data-end="3171"><td>102</td><td>Drama</td></tr><tr data-start="3172" data-end="3193"><td>103</td><td>Music</td></body></table><p data-start="3195" data-end="3223">âœ” <strong data-start="3197" data-end="3221">Club-President Table</strong></p><table data-start="3224" data-end="3326"><thead data-start="3224" data-end="3251"><tr data-start="3224" data-end="3251"><th data-start="3224" data-end="3233">Club</th><th data-start="3233" data-end="3251">Club_President</th></tr></thead><tbody data-start="3277" data-end="3326"><tr data-start="3277" data-end="3301"><td>Music</td><td>Alice</td></tr><tr data-start="3302" data-end="3326"><td>Drama</td><td>Bob</td></tr></tbody></table><p data-start="3328" data-end="3362">âœ… Now, the tables are in <strong data-start="3353" data-end="3361">BCNF</strong>.</p><hr data-start="3364" data-end="3367"><h2 data-start="3369" data-end="3389"><strong data-start="3372" data-end="3389">Summary Table</strong></h2><table data-start="3390" data-end="3986"><thead data-start="3390" data-end="3441"><tr data-start="3390" data-end="3441"><th data-start="3390" data-end="3411"><strong data-start="3392" data-end10">Violation Type</strong></th><th data-start="3411" data-end="3425"><strong data-start="3413" data-end="3424">Example</strong></th><th data-start="3425" data-end="3441"><strong data-start="3427" data-end="3439">Solution</strong></th></tr></thead><tbody data-start="3492" data-end="3986"><tr data-start="3492" data-end="3667"><td><strong data-start="3494" data-end="3570">One attribute functionally determines another but is not a candidate key</strong></td><td><code data-start="3573" data-end="3596">Classroom â†’ Professor</code></td><td>Split into <strong data-start="3610" data-end="3630">Professor-Course</strong> and <strong data-start="3635" data-end="3658">Classroom-Professor</strong> tables</td></tr><tr data-start="3668" data-end="3836"><td><strong data-start="3670" data-end="3700">Overlapping candidate keys</strong></td><td><code data-start="3703" data-end="3727">{Employee_ID, Project}</code> and <code data-start="3732" data-end="3752">{Project, Manager}</code> both act as keys</td><td>Split into <strong ta-start="3783" data-end="3803">Employee-Project</strong> and <strong data-start="3808" data-end="3827">Project-Manager</strong> tables</td></tr><tr data-start="3837" data-end="3986"><td><strong data-start="3839" data-end="3898">One column uniquely determines another but is not a key</strong></td><td><code data-start="3901" data-end="3924">Club â†’ Club_President</code></td><td>Split into <strong data-start="3938" data-end="3954">Student-Club</strong> and <strong data-start="3959" data-end="3977">Club-President</strong> tables</td></tr></tbody></table><p data-start="3988" data-end="4048" data-is-last-node="" data-is-only-node="">Would you like further breakdowns or real-world examples? ğŸ˜Š</p></div>